				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ Methylation\operatorname{} Measur{e}_{CpG}={\displaystyle \sum_{fragments\  near\ CpG}}\hat{P}\left( Fragment\  covers\  the\ CpG\right). $$\end{document}MethylationMeasureCpG=∑fragmentsnearCpGP^FragmentcoverstheCpG.

The Benjamini–Hochberg FDR control procedure works as follows. First, the p values in each group were ordered in increasing order: P(1), P(2), …, P(m). Next, the maximum k is selected such that \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {P}_{(k)}\le \frac{k}{m}\alpha $$\end{document}Pk≤kmα. The tests with smallest k p values are then declared to have FDR below α. In our case α = 0.01 (i.e., 1 %).
